<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Snow Geese</DIV><br>
<br /> 
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<i>for Charles Beck </i><br /> <br /> 

The flock is whorled like a translucent shell<br /> 
and intricate as the tubing of a horn,<br /> 
its embouchure, the soft foot of a snail<br /> 
lighting on sand, except the sand is corn,<br /> 
chisel ploughed and left to build the soil<br /> 
from which indebted farmers have been torn. <br /> 
<br /> 
I catch one note—a wild, wayfaring cry<br /> 
as snow geese splash into a glacial mere.<br /> 
Framed by moraines under a nacreous sky,<br /> 
they echo in the chambers of my ear.<br /> 
How does an ear rival your artist's eye<br /> 
that sees what I can only hope to hear? <br /> 
<br><br>

<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('murphy')">by Tim Murphy</a><br><br><br>
<br />
</td></tr></table><br><br>
<br>
  <img src="images/snowgeese.jpg"><br>
  <a class="artistline" href="javascript:goauthor('zirilli');">art by Donald Zirilli</a><br>
